title: aim-9_sidewinder
body:
The AIM-9 Sidewinder (for Air Intercept Missile) is a short-range air-to-air [[missile]] which entered service with the [[united_states_navy|US Navy]] in 1956 and subsequently was adopted by the [[united_states_air_force|US Air Force]] in 1964. Since then the Sidewinder has proved to be an enduring international success, and its latest variants remain standard equipment in most western-aligned air forces. The [[Soviet]] K-13, a reverse-engineered copy of the AIM-9, was also widely adopted by a number of nations.

The Sidewinder is the most widely used air-to-air missile in the West, with more than 110,000 missiles produced for the U.S. and 27 other nations, of which perhaps one percent have been used in combat. It has been built under license by some other nations including [[Sweden]], and can even equip on [[helicopter|helicopters]], such as the Bell AH-1Z Viper. The AIM-9 is one of the oldest, lowest cost, and most successful air-to-air missiles, with an estimated 270 [[aircraft]] kills in its history of use. When firing a Sidewinder, NATO pilots use the brevity code FOX-2.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: AIM-9 Sidewinder":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AIM-9_Sidewinder]

title: patria_pasi
body:
The Patria Pasi (earlier known as the Sisu Pasi) is a Finnish-made six-wheeled [[armored personnel carrier]] (APC) originally designed for Finnish Defence Forces.

The basic appearance and configuration of Patria Pasi is similar to most wheeled APCs. The XA-180 and XA-185 versions are fully amphibious while the XA-203 is not.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: Patria Pasi":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patria_Pasi]

title: aim-120_amraam
body:
Advanced Medium-Range Air-to-Air [[Missile]], or AMRAAM (pronounced AM-ram), is an American beyond-visual-range air-to-air [[missile]] (BVRAAM) capable of all-weather day-and-night operations.

Designed with a 7-inch (180 mm) diameter, and employing active transmit-receive radar guidance instead of semi-active receive-only radar guidance, it has the advantage of being a fire-and-forget weapon when compared to the previous generation [[aim-7_sparrow|Aim-7 Sparrow]] missile. 

When an AMRAAM [[missile]] is launched, NATO pilots use the brevity code Fox Three.

h4. External links

* "Wikipedia: AIM-120 AMRAAM":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AIM-120_AMRAAM]

title: rinoa_heartilly
body:
Rinoa Heartilly is a female protagonist and playable character from [[Final Fantasy VIII]]. She is best known for her trademark [[angel wings]] printed on the back of her [[sleeveless duster]] sweater and, as such, her "character symbol" is a white feather that signifies the wings. She is [[Squall Leonhart]]'s love interest, and is featured in the game's logo with him. 

She has medium-length [[black hair]] and [[brown eyes]]. Her outfit consists of [[arm warmers]], a blue [[sleeveless]] [[open clothes|open]]  [[coat]], [[bike shorts]], [[denim skirt]], and a black [[undershirt]]. She also has a [[black ribbon]] on her left forearm.

title: commissar
body:
Power sword, mini-rocket-firing pistol and a big cool hat. Et voila, you have just got yourself one of the most badass normal humans ever to exist in the whole grimdark nightmare that is [[Warhammer 40k]].

Imperial Guardsmen are tough and loyal to the Imperium, but a good [b][s]BLAM[/s][/b] encouragement from a Commissar will ensure the troopers' morale always remains at one thousand percent. That pretty much sums up the job of an average Commissar: making sure that the men (and women) hold the line at all cost. These cool-hat zealots are also very quick to be on the triggers at the slightest notions of cowardice, Chaos taint or even donning your uniforms the wrong way; but their presence on the battlefield is nonetheless much appreciated due to their aforementioned role. After all, aren't they the ones that ensure us puny humans actually stand our ground against all kind of Eldritch abominations that the universe throws at us and even [i]duke it out[/i]?

• [[Astra Militarum]]

title: lasgun
body:
[i]We bring the light of the Immortal God Emperor to the furthest parts of the Galaxy[/i]

[b]Lasgun[/b] or otherwise known as [b]Lasrifle[/b] is one of the two inseparable items (with the other being the [s]T-shirt[/s] ceramite vest) of the trillions of Imperial Guardsmen out there fighting for the Imperium Of Man. While the weapon lacks the stopping power comparing to the Bolter or T'au Railgun, its ease of production, the lack of ammunition requirement, and most important of all, the sheer amount of Imperial Guardsmen will more or less make up for the Lasgun shortcoming.

After all, nothing beats unleashing an ocean of metal-melting laser bolts in the face of your opponent.

•[[Astra Militarum]]

title: f-15_eagle
body:
The [b]Boeing F-15 Eagle[/b] is a twin-engined [[fighter jet]] developed by McDonnell Douglas (now part of Boeing). It is one of the most easily recognized of the "Teen" series of fighters, with its prominent bubble canopy, dual vertical tailfins, sawtoothed elevators, and broad delta wing. It was designed in the 1960-1970s under the Fighter Experimental program as a replacement for the [[F-4 Phantom II]] and to counter aircraft like the [[MiG-25]] with record-setting climb performance and impressive top speed while retaining good dogfight capability. Sometimes called the "Twin-tailed Tennis Court," due to its large size.

The air superiority models' armament includes air-to-air missiles and an internal 20mm cannon. The F-15E Strike Eagle variant, optimized for ground attack missions, carries an additional crew member in a second seat.

body: Tracheotomy, or tracheostomy, is a surgical procedure which consists of making an incision (cut) on the anterior aspect (front) of the neck and opening a direct airway through an incision in the trachea (windpipe). A [i][[Kemono Friends]][/i] character. One of many "Friends" in Japari Park. The Thoroughbred Trio were created for a promotion involving the Anime and the [[Japan Racing Association]]. They have since integrated with the wider franchise and the JRA moved on with [[umamusume|a different franchise]].

Horses and Thoroughbreds are better explained in [[Brown Thoroughbred (Kemono Friends)|]]'s page.

A "chestnut" horse denotes a horse with a reddish-brown coat and mane without any black hair at the limbs. There are variants such as flaxen chestnut (chestnuts with manes and tails better described as blonde or a lighter red) and liver chestnut (chestnuts with a particularly dark coat). Flaxen liver chestnuts are simply a combination of the two.

Chestnut Thoroughbred is (naturally) a [[horse girl]] with long brown hair resembling a mane in a ponytail with a white stripe on the bangs (a "blaze" marking), wearing a brown sports ensemble.

body:
A type of tuned [[percussion_instrument]], chimes are a set of objects which produce sound when struck, suspended from a frame made of wood or metal. These objects are different lengths or sizes to produce specific pitches. There are two main types, both made with metal tubes: a small set of chimes suspended from a length of wood that makes a sound resembling a [[wind_chime]]; and a large set of chimes hung in a metal frame that sound like church bells when struck with a mallet. title: tachibana_chitose
body:
Chitose Tachibana is a hostile female spirit in Fatal Frame II: Crimson Butterfly. The younger sister of Itsuki and Mutsuki Tachibana, Chitose was not a twin and knew very little about the Crimson Sacrifice Ritual nor did she understand where Mutsuki had gone and why Itsuki's hair had turned white.

Chitose had poor eyesight, and was often frightened of strangers, frequently hiding inside of closets when they came to her home. Because of this, Itsuki gave her a bell to wear, so that he may know when she was in danger and could go to her aid. Before leaving to help Yae and Sae Kurosawa escape the village, Itsuki gave Chitose the key to his room, with instructions to give it to his friend, Ryozo Munakata. When Ryozo came, however, Chitose got so scared that she hid, unable to give him the key. After the escape attempt, Chitose blamed Yae for having Itsuki wrongfully imprisoned, not understanding how much he wanted to help them escape.

When Sae's ritual failed and the Repentance occurred, Chitose hid inside of a cupboard to escape the coming darkness. She became trapped inside, however, and panicked, scrawling "help me" on the walls and frantically calling out for help from her brother. In the end she either starved to death or was swallowed up by the darkness.

Chitose wears a distinct crimson kimono, with pale gold butterfly designs, further alluding the game's theme. Like all ghosts, she appears very pale, and she keeps a sad expression on her face. Chitose also wears a bell on her right wrist, which chimes whenever she is present in the room, even while she is hiding.

title: agm-65_maverick
body:
The AGM-65 Maverick is an air-to-ground [[missile]] (AGM) designed for close air support. It is the most widely produced precision-guided [[missile]] in the Western world, and is effective against a wide range of tactical targets, including armor, air defenses, ships, ground transportation and fuel storage facilities.

Development began in 1966 at Hughes as the first missile to use an electronic contrast seeker. It entered service with the [[United States Air Force]] in August 1972. Since then, it has been exported to more than 30 countries and is certified on 25 aircraft. The Maverick served during the Vietnam, Yom Kippur, Iran–Iraq, and Persian Gulf Wars, along with other smaller conflicts, destroying enemy forces and installations with varying degrees of success.

Since its introduction into service, numerous Maverick versions had been designed and produced using electro-optical, laser, and imaging infrared guidance systems. The AGM-65 has two types of warhead: one has a contact fuze in the nose, the other has a heavyweight warhead fitted with a delayed-action fuze, which penetrates the target with its kinetic energy before detonating. The missile is currently produced by Raytheon Missile Systems.

The Maverick shares the same configuration as Hughes's AIM-4 Falcon and [[AIM-54 Phoenix]], and measures more than 2.4 m (8 ft) in length and 30 cm (12 in) in diameter.

"Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AGM-65_Maverick]

Shibasaki Saki is a [[yuru-chara]] from the Shibasaki area of Chōfu, Tokyo.


Saki's motif is a [[Shiba Inu]], from the word "Shiba" in Shibasaki, and her pink body is inspired by the Chōfu city flower "Hyakkini". At first glance, she looks like an angel or a dog or a cat with wings, but the parts that look like wings are the curly hairs unique unique to the appearance of the [[komainu]]. At the time of the character's birth, there were no character-related events in the city, so she mainly appeared in events outside of Chōfu in Tokyo. Because of this, she has a long-distance relationship with other yuru-charas, and is in a long-distance relationship with "Aman the Hoshi", a character from Katano City, Osaka Prefecture. Her favorite game is Capcom's [[Ookami (game)|]] and she looks up to the main character, [[Amaterasu (ookami)|]].

title: zed_(wild_arms)
body:
One of the antagonists of the Playstation game [[Wild Arms 1]] and its Playstation 2 remake Wild Arms: Alter Code F. He also makes a cameo in [[Wild Arms 5]].

Zed is a Metal Demon working for Zeikfried, who strives to become one of the Quarter Knights. He isn't taken very seriously, and Zed fights the party numerous times to accomplish his goals. While he is a powerful opponent, he mainly acts as the game's comic relief.

Ultimately, Zed gives up on being a Quarter Knight, but when he finds the blind girl [[Aura (Wild Arms)|Aura]] living alone in Saint Centaur, he protects her from outside threats. In this regard, he finally becomes the great person he always wanted to be (if only in his mind).

In both versions, Zed can be fought as an optional boss in Saint Centaur, but the outcomes are different. In the original, he gives [[Jack Van Burace]] his sword Doom Bringer. In the remake, he joins the party.

title: f6f_hellcat
body:
A [[World War II]] single-seat carrier-based fighter manufactured by Grumman and employed primarily by the US Navy. Powered by a 2,100 hp (1,567 kW) "radial engine":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pratt_%26_Whitney_R-2800, it was armed with .50-caliber [[machine gun|machine guns]] and/or 20mm cannon and could carry up to 2,000 lbs (907 kg) of rockets, bombs, or torpedoes. Virtually all in-service [[airplane|airplanes]] were painted some shade of blue.

The F6F proved to be a reliable and effective plane, owning to its durable airframe. The plane outclassed the Japanese [[A6M Zero]] in almost every aspect (save for manoverability) and became the most effective naval figher of the war. Claiming 5,157 recorded aerial victories.
